@tonybaloney - responding to https://github.com/apache/libcloud/pull/666#issuecomment-166802455

Google Container Engine (GKE) is our hosted / managed version of Kubernetes. When you spin up a GKE cluster, it provisions VMs with k8s pre-installed and exposes the k8s API endpoint. After the GKE cluster is up, you interact directly with the [k8s API](http://kubernetes.io/v1.1/api-ref.html) for deploying / managing apps (docker images) using native resources like Pods, ReplicationControllers, Services, etc. Interaction with the k8s API endpoint is done either with `kubectl` or REST. At no point do you interact directly with Docker.

So, in terms of what you have for CaaS so far, I'd say it fits very well with GKE w.r.t to cluster CRUD operations, but not so much w.r.t underlying kubernetes (e.g. `install_image` or `list_image`). I supposed you could implement `deploy_container` such that it would, for k8s, deploy the specified docker image inside of a k8s Pod and have many `ex_` params. But I'm not sure how this would work well with other k8s resources.

@erjohnso in the driver you connect to the API server of the cluster. When you run list_clusters they equate to namespaces. When you ask to list_containers it looks at all the pods in that cluster (namespace) and lists all the containers within them. 
If you deploy a container to a cluster it creates a single container pod for that container and places it into the namespace. 
list_locations will be the method to show the clusters in GKE. You can provision a cluster to those locations in the API.
